      "writtenOn": "2026-07-14T02:57:55Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "@paligill@gmail.com, thanks for the clear explanation and the nomenclature suggestion! It makes sense for our customized version-read logic requirements.\n\nI have updated the schema in the latest patchset. I kept the existing IntelSPIFlash to avoid any breaking changes for current users, and added IntelHostSPIFlash following your \u003cvendor\u003eHostSpiFlash format.",
      "parentUuid": "047833c0_47815dcb",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a93e42c2_36b9dbce",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000153
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-14T16:23:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Should we handle that through Compatible?\n\nnot in the way EM is set up today.  Intent is top level types carry the definition, and similarities are handled by deduplicating code in the reactors.",
      "parentUuid": "42c0da88_f8b52543",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4f538b21_d9f2a784",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001712
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-15T12:06:06Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e to lock onto specific devices and trigger customized behaviors such as version get.\n\nCan this be broken out? For example by having a `VersionBehavior` property that determines how the version is supposed to be obtained.\n\n\u003e Should we handle that through Compatible?\n\nThis is how compatbiles look like:\n```\n\nanacapa/anacapa_mb_evt1.json\n\"CompatibleHardware\": \"com.meta.Hardware.Anacapa.CPLD.LFMXO5_15D_mb_evt1\",\n\"CompatibleHardware\": \"com.meta.Hardware.Anacapa.VR.MP2869_pvddcr_cpu0_p0\",\n\"CompatibleHardware\": \"com.meta.Hardware.Anacapa.VR.MP29612_pvddcr_cpu1_p0\",\n\"CompatibleHardware\": \"com.meta.Hardware.Anacapa.VR.MP29612_pvddcr_soc_p0\",\n```\n\nSo as a result we would be making platform specific lookup tables in the reactor or do string manipulations to extract something from the compatible string which could have been a separate configuration property (avoiding the need for string manipulations)\n\nNot saying it can\u0027t be done but having a separate property to cover the specific use-case (how to query the version) would be simpler.",
      "parentUuid": "a93e42c2_36b9dbce",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f5ec0341_9214fb7b",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 11,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001758
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-15T17:39:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Can this be broken out? For example by having a VersionBehavior property that determines how the version is supposed to be obtained.\n\nI would prefer not to make any such changes and let the backend decide what to do based on EM Type, which is being done for other updaters too. These topics have been discussed in past with EM maintainers (No Subtypes, type needs to carry relevant information) and its being done this way for that reason.\n\n\n\u003e I have updated the schema in the latest patchset. I kept the existing IntelSPIFlash to avoid any breaking changes for current users, and added IntelHostSPIFlash following your \u003cvendor\u003eHostSpiFlash format.\n\n@Kyle.Hsieh@quantatw.com We don\u0027t need IntelSPIFlash. You can change it to IntelHostSPIFlash. I don\u0027t see anyone using it in EM Configs. But you will need to update it in backend where the right tools get selected.",
      "parentUuid": "4f538b21_d9f2a784",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 7,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 11,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "629c6caf_73c73041",
        "filename": "schemas/firmware.json",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 84,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000153
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-07-13T18:30:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The intent here was to differentiate between the various types of SPI flash.  Intel spi flash is laid out differently than AMD, is laid out differently than an FPGA.  The intent is that we could differentiate and add things like validity checks in the future.\n\nI suspect you want to change this to \u003cHostSOCManufacturer\u003eSpiFlash",
      "revId": "7ededf61f85edc96ebb92629c6e4b031ba5d8eea",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4c3c7156_cb4e6e74",
        "filename": "schemas/firmware.json",
